        "assistant_drafted_requirements_count": 13,
        "assistant_drafted_requirements_summary": "Define the GTM showcase as a bounded multi-service system, not a general GTM super-agent: The product must provide a governed GTM agent system composed of explicit bounded service areas for pipeline analytics, enrichment, prioritization, outreach drafting, and operational previews. It must answer recurring GTM business questions through declared capabilities rather than unconstrained CRM, warehouse, SQL, or prompt-driven exploration. The system must preserve explicit service ownership and must not collapse into a generic query-anything or do-anything surface.\nPreserve the canonical capability contract across design, generation, and verification: The product must preserve the canonical public capability contract defined for the showcase so that PM requirements, developer design, generated implementations, runtime metadata, and regression validation all refer to the same governed behaviors. Accepted requirements should make clear that these capabilities are stable contract surface, remain owned by their designated service areas, and are not replaced by paraphrased identifiers in downstream artifacts.\nMake actor-aware visibility, scope, and outcome differences explicit: The product must support actor-aware governance that changes what data is visible, what fields are masked, what scope is allowed, what actions can be prepared, and when requests are denied or require approval. Requirements should explicitly cover actor-sensitive outcomes such as restricted regional scope, masked financial values, and different allowed preparation behavior for different actor families.\nRequire explicit governed outcomes instead of silent guessing or overreach: Every bounded capability must produce one of a small set of reviewable governed outcomes: success for in-scope reads or drafts, clarification when critical inputs are missing, restriction when the actor is only partially allowed, denial for unsafe or out-of-scope requests, and approval_required for operational previews that stop before execution. The system must not silently guess missing critical fields or improvise unsupported behavior.\nRequire clarification for missing critical scope such as quarter, cohort, account reference, or target: The product must ask for clarification when a request omits critical scope needed for a bounded answer. This includes missing quarter for pipeline analytics and operational previews, missing account set or reference account for enrichment, missing cohort or routing target for prioritization, and missing target, persona, channel, or objective for outreach drafting. The system must not infer these fields when the business specs require explicit scope.\nSupport bounded pipeline analytics views with explainable summaries and contributors: The product must support bounded pipeline analytics capabilities that answer recurring GTM review questions for a quarter and optional allowed scope. Accepted requirements should cover forecast summaries with declared forecast modes, stage bottleneck summaries with one bounded slice dimension, sales team performance summaries with one bounded slice dimension, and product pipeline summaries with optional product focus. These views must return explainable rollups, evidence, or top contributors rather than raw row-level exports.\nSupport bounded account enrichment and lookalike analysis without becoming a raw enrichment surface: The product must let users request bounded enrichment summaries for a selected account set, explain why an account is a strong or weak fit, and identify lookalike accounts using bounded similarity logic. It must stay within explicit account or segment scope, remain read-only in this phase, and deny raw bulk enrichment exports or requests that drift into outreach, scoring, or operational mutation.\nSupport governed prioritization with explainable ranking and routing posture recommendations: The product must score a bounded cohort of leads or accounts, rank the highest-priority items with bounded rationale, and recommend routing posture such as sales, nurture, or archive. It must deny requests for raw model-feature or training-detail exports, must not silently route or mutate downstream systems, and must stop at approval_required when a request moves from recommendation into routing execution.\nKeep outreach bounded to draft preparation and variants, not send execution: The product must draft bounded outreach content for an explicit lead or account target, support follow-up and objection-response variants, and tailor drafts using explicit context. It must ask for clarification when target or message intent is unclear, deny send requests and raw transcript or training-corpus export requests, and remain draft-only in the first cut without mutating CRM engagement state.\nSeparate operational preparation from execution with a hard approval boundary: The product must support bounded operational previews such as reassignment planning, follow-up preparation, and routing preparation, but it must stop before any downstream write or ownership change. Requirements should state that preview generation is allowed only within actor authority, that the next step returns approval_required, and that direct execution requests are denied or stopped rather than carried out automatically.\nSupport governed cross-service composition without hiding policy in app glue: The product must support compound GTM questions that span more than one bounded service hop, such as pipeline or risk to enrichment, prioritization to enrichment to outreach, forecast to risk to follow-up preview, score to route, and bottleneck to risk to enrichment. These flows must preserve service-owned capability boundaries, actor-aware restrictions, clarification behavior, denial behavior, and approval stops at the correct step rather than relying on hidden consumer-side logic.\nRequire auditability for every governed call and actor-differentiated result: The product must make every governed call reconstructable after the fact. Requirements should state that the system can explain who asked, which actor identity applied, which capability ran, which parameters were used after normalization, what governed outcome occurred, and why different actors may have received different results. Auditability must be treated as part of the business trust story, not only as an implementation detail.\nMake the full business-to-runtime validation path a product requirement: The product must make the full lifecycle visible and reviewable: source business specs as first-class artifacts, PM-readable requirements derived from those specs, developer design derived from accepted requirements, generated code used in the running implementation, explicit extension points outside overwritten generated files, runtime metadata that Studio can inspect, and regression-backed validation across single-service and compound flows. Requirements should also distinguish what the BI verification surface can validate versus what remains unique to governed ANIP runtime behavior."
